{name: "COMPASS_ORIENT", key: "COMPASS_ORIENT", description: "Compass orientation", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "None", "1": "Yaw45", "2": "Yaw90", "3": "Yaw135", "4": "Yaw180", "5": "Yaw225", "6": "Yaw270", "7": "Yaw315", "8": "Roll180", "9": "Roll180Yaw45", "10": "Roll180Yaw90", "11": "Roll180Yaw135", "12": "Pitch180", "13": "Roll180Yaw225", "14": "Roll180Yaw270", "15": "Roll180Yaw315", "16": "Roll90", "17": "Roll90Yaw45", "18": "Roll90Yaw90", "19": "Roll90Yaw135", "20": "Roll270", "21": "Roll270Yaw45", "22": "Roll270Yaw90", "23": "Roll270Yaw136", "24": "Pitch90", "25": "Pitch270", "26": "Pitch180Yaw90", "27": "Pitch180Yaw270", "28": "Roll90Pitch90", "29": "Roll180Pitch90", "30": "Roll270Pitch90", "31": "Roll90Pitch180", "32": "Roll270Pitch180", "33": "Roll90Pitch270", "34": "Roll180Pitch270", "35": "Roll270Pitch270", "36": "Roll90Pitch180Yaw90", "37": "Roll90Yaw270", "38": "Yaw293Pitch68Roll90"},
documentation: "The orientation of the compass relative to the autopilot board. This will default to the right value for each board type, but can be changed if you have an external compass. See the documentation for your external compass for the right value. The correct orientation should give the X axis forward, the Y axis to the right and the Z axis down. So if your aircraft is pointing west it should show a positive value for the Y axis, and a value close to zero for the X axis. On a PX4 or Pixhawk with an external compass the correct value is zero if the compass is correctly oriented. NOTE: This orientation is combined with any AHRS_ORIENTATION setting."},

{name: "INS_STILL_THRESH", key: "INS_STILL_THRESH", description: "Stillness threshold for detecting if we are moving", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.05 50", documentation: "Threshold to tolerate vibration to determine if vehicle is motionless. Suggested values: Planes/rover use 0.1, multirotors use 1, tradHeli uses 5"},
{name: "INS_GYR_CAL", key: "INS_GYR_CAL", description: "Gyro Calibration scheme", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "Never", " 1": "Start-up only"},

{name: "INS_TRIM_OPTION", key: "INS_TRIM_OPTION", description: "Accel cal trim option", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "Dont adjust the trims", "1": "Assume first orientation was level", "2": "Assume ACC_BODYFIX is perfectly aligned to the vehicle"},
documentation: "Specifies how the accel cal routine determines the trims"},
{name: "INS_ACC_BODYFIX", key: "INS_ACC_BODYFIX", description: "Body-fixed accelerometer", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"1": "IMU 1", "2": "IMU 2", "3": "IMU 3"},
documentation: "The body-fixed accelerometer to be used for trim calculation"},
{name: "AHRS_GPS_GAIN", key: "AHRS_GPS_GAIN", description: "AHRS GPS gain", value: "", user: "", range: "0.0 1.0", increment: ".01", documentation: "This controls how how much to use the GPS to correct the attitude. This should never be set to zero for a plane as it would result in the plane losing control in turns. For a plane please use the default value of 1.0."},
{name: "AHRS_GPS_USE", key: "AHRS_GPS_USE", description: "AHRS use GPS for navigation", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "Disabled", "1": "Enabled"},
documentation: "This controls whether to use dead-reckoning or GPS based navigation. If set to 0 then the GPS wont be used for navigation, and only dead reckoning will be used. A value of zero should never be used for normal flight."},
{name: "AHRS_YAW_P", key: "AHRS_YAW_P", description: "Yaw P", value: "", user: "", range: "0.1 0.4", increment: ".01", documentation: "This controls the weight the compass or GPS has on the heading. A higher value means the heading will track the yaw source (GPS or compass) more rapidly."},
{name: "AHRS_RP_P", key: "AHRS_RP_P", description: "AHRS RP_P", value: "", user: "", range: "0.1 0.4", increment: ".01", documentation: "This controls how fast the accelerometers correct the attitude"},
{name: "AHRS_WIND_MAX", key: "AHRS_WIND_MAX", description: "Maximum wind", value: "", user: "", range: "0 127", increment: "1", units: "m/s", documentation: "This sets the maximum allowable difference between ground speed and airspeed. This allows the plane to cope with a failing airspeed sensor. A value of zero means to use the airspeed as is."},
{name: "AHRS_TRIM_X", key: "AHRS_TRIM_X", description: "AHRS Trim Roll", value: "", user: "User", range: "-0.1745 +0.1745", increment: "0.01", units: "radians", documentation: "Compensates for the roll angle difference between the control board and the frame. Positive values make the vehicle roll right."},
{name: "AHRS_TRIM_Y", key: "AHRS_TRIM_Y", description: "AHRS Trim Pitch", value: "", user: "User", range: "-0.1745 +0.1745", increment: "0.01", units: "radians", documentation: "Compensates for the pitch angle difference between the control board and the frame. Positive values make the vehicle pitch up/back."},
{name: "AHRS_TRIM_Z", key: "AHRS_TRIM_Z", description: "AHRS Trim Yaw", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "-0.1745 +0.1745", increment: "0.01", units: "radians", documentation: "Not Used"},
{name: "AHRS_ORIENTATION", key: "AHRS_ORIENTATION", description: "Board Orientation", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "None", "1": "Yaw45", "2": "Yaw90", "3": "Yaw135", "4": "Yaw180", "5": "Yaw225", "6": "Yaw270", "7": "Yaw315", "8": "Roll180", "9": "Roll180Yaw45", "10": "Roll180Yaw90", "11": "Roll180Yaw135", "12": "Pitch180", "13": "Roll180Yaw225", "14": "Roll180Yaw270", "15": "Roll180Yaw315", "16": "Roll90", "17": "Roll90Yaw45", "18": "Roll90Yaw90", "19": "Roll90Yaw135", "20": "Roll270", "21": "Roll270Yaw45", "22": "Roll270Yaw90", "23": "Roll270Yaw136", "24": "Pitch90", "25": "Pitch270", "26": "Pitch180Yaw90", "27": "Pitch180Yaw270", "28": "Roll90Pitch90", "29": "Roll180Pitch90", "30": "Roll270Pitch90", "31": "Roll90Pitch180", "32": "Roll270Pitch180", "33": "Roll90Pitch270", "34": "Roll180Pitch270", "35": "Roll270Pitch270", "36": "Roll90Pitch180Yaw90", "37": "Roll90Yaw270"},
documentation: "Overall board orientation relative to the standard orientation for the board type. This rotates the IMU and compass readings to allow the board to be oriented in your vehicle at any 90 or 45 degree angle. This option takes affect on next boot. After changing you will need to re-level your vehicle."},
{name: "AHRS_COMP_BETA", key: "AHRS_COMP_BETA", description: "AHRS Velocity Complementary Filter Beta Coefficient", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.001 0.5", increment: ".01", documentation: "This controls the time constant for the cross-over frequency used to fuse AHRS (airspeed and heading) and GPS data to estimate ground velocity. Time constant is 0.1/beta. A larger time constant will use GPS data less and a small time constant will use air data less."},
{name: "AHRS_GPS_MINSATS", key: "AHRS_GPS_MINSATS", description: "AHRS GPS Minimum satellites", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0 10", increment: "1", documentation: "Minimum number of satellites visible to use GPS for velocity based corrections attitude correction. This defaults to 6, which is about the point at which the velocity numbers from a GPS become too unreliable for accurate correction of the accelerometers."},
{name: "AHRS_EKF_TYPE", key: "AHRS_EKF_TYPE", description: "Use NavEKF Kalman filter for attitude and position estimation", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "Disabled", "1": "Enabled", "2": "Enable EKF2"},
documentation: "This controls whether the NavEKF Kalman filter is used for attitude and position estimation and whether fallback to the DCM algorithm is allowed. Note that on copters disabled is not available, and will be the same as enabled - no fallback"},
{name: "ARSPD_ENABLE", key: "ARSPD_ENABLE", description: "Airspeed enable", value: "", user: "", values: {"0": "Disable", "1": "Enable"},
documentation: "enable airspeed sensor"},
{name: "ARSPD_USE", key: "ARSPD_USE", description: "Airspeed use", value: "", user: "", values: {"1": "Use", "0": "Dont Use"},
documentation: "use airspeed for flight control"},
{name: "ARSPD_OFFSET", key: "ARSPD_OFFSET", description: "Airspeed offset", value: "", user: "", increment: "0.1", documentation: "Airspeed calibration offset"},
{name: "ARSPD_RATIO", key: "ARSPD_RATIO", description: "Airspeed ratio", value: "", user: "", increment: "0.1", documentation: "Airspeed calibration ratio"},
{name: "ARSPD_PIN", key: "ARSPD_PIN", description: "Airspeed pin", value: "", user: "Advanced", documentation: "The analog pin number that the airspeed sensor is connected to. Set this to 0..9 for the APM2 analog pins. Set to 64 on an APM1 for the dedicated airspeed port on the end of the board. Set to 11 on PX4 for the analog airspeed port. Set to 15 on the Pixhawk for the analog airspeed port. Set to 65 on the PX4 or Pixhawk for an EagleTree or MEAS I2C airspeed sensor."},
{name: "ARSPD_AUTOCAL", key: "ARSPD_AUTOCAL", description: "Automatic airspeed ratio calibration", value: "", user: "Advanced", documentation: "If this is enabled then the APM will automatically adjust the ARSPD_RATIO during flight, based upon an estimation filter using ground speed and true airspeed. The automatic calibration will save the new ratio to EEPROM every 2 minutes if it changes by more than 5%. This option should be enabled for a calibration flight then disabled again when calibration is complete. Leaving it enabled all the time is not recommended."},
{name: "ARSPD_TUBE_ORDER", key: "ARSPD_TUBE_ORDER", description: "Control pitot tube order", value: "", user: "Advanced", documentation: "This parameter allows you to control whether the order in which the tubes are attached to your pitot tube matters. If you set this to 0 then the top connector on the sensor needs to be the dynamic pressure. If set to 1 then the bottom connector needs to be the dynamic pressure. If set to 2 (the default) then the airspeed driver will accept either order. The reason you may wish to specify the order is it will allow your airspeed sensor to detect if the aircraft it receiving excessive pressure on the static port, which would otherwise be seen as a positive airspeed."},
{name: "ARSPD_SKIP_CAL", key: "ARSPD_SKIP_CAL", description: "Skip airspeed calibration on startup", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "Disable", "1": "Enable"},
documentation: "This parameter allows you to skip airspeed offset calibration on startup, instead using the offset from the last calibration. This may be desirable if the offset variance between flights for your sensor is low and you want to avoid having to cover the pitot tube on each boot."},
{name: "NAVL1_PERIOD", key: "NAVL1_PERIOD", description: "L1 control period", value: "", user: "", range: "1 60", increment: "1", units: "seconds", documentation: "Period in seconds of L1 tracking loop. This parameter is the primary control for agressiveness of turns in auto mode. This needs to be larger for less responsive airframes. The default of 20 is quite conservative, but for most RC aircraft will lead to reasonable flight. For smaller more agile aircraft a value closer to 15 is appropriate, or even as low as 10 for some very agile aircraft. When tuning, change this value in small increments, as a value that is much too small (say 5 or 10 below the right value) can lead to very radical turns, and a risk of stalling."},
{name: "NAVL1_DAMPING", key: "NAVL1_DAMPING", description: "L1 control damping ratio", value: "", user: "", range: "0.6 1.0", increment: "0.05", documentation: "Damping ratio for L1 control. Increase this in increments of 0.05 if you are getting overshoot in path tracking. You should not need a value below 0.7 or above 0.85."},
{name: "NAVL1_XTRACK_I", key: "NAVL1_XTRACK_I", description: "L1 control crosstrack integrator gain", value: "", user: "", range: "0 0.1", increment: "0.01", documentation: "Crosstrack error integrator gain. This gain is applied to the crosstrack error to ensure it converges to zero. Set to zero to disable. Smaller values converge slower, higher values will cause crosstrack error oscillation."},
{name: "TECS_CLMB_MAX", key: "TECS_CLMB_MAX", description: "Maximum Climb Rate (metres/sec)", value: "", user: "User", range: "0.1 20.0", increment: "0.1", documentation: "This is the best climb rate that the aircraft can achieve with the throttle set to THR_MAX and the airspeed set to the default value. For electric aircraft make sure this number can be achieved towards the end of flight when the battery voltage has reduced. The setting of this parameter can be checked by commanding a positive altitude change of 100m in loiter, RTL or guided mode. If the throttle required to climb is close to THR_MAX and the aircraft is maintaining airspeed, then this parameter is set correctly. If the airspeed starts to reduce, then the parameter is set to high, and if the throttle demand require to climb and maintain speed is noticeably less than THR_MAX, then either CLMB_MAX should be increased or THR_MAX reduced."},
{name: "TECS_SINK_MIN", key: "TECS_SINK_MIN", description: "Minimum Sink Rate (metres/sec)", value: "", user: "User", range: "0.1 10.0", increment: "0.1", documentation: "This is the sink rate of the aircraft with the throttle set to THR_MIN and the same airspeed as used to measure CLMB_MAX."},
{name: "TECS_TIME_CONST", key: "TECS_TIME_CONST", description: "Controller time constant (sec)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "3.0 10.0", increment: "0.2", documentation: "This is the time constant of the TECS control algorithm. Smaller values make it faster to respond, large values make it slower to respond."},
{name: "TECS_THR_DAMP", key: "TECS_THR_DAMP", description: "Controller throttle damping", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.1 1.0", increment: "0.1", documentation: "This is the damping gain for the throttle demand loop. Increase to add damping  to correct for oscillations in speed and height."},
{name: "TECS_INTEG_GAIN", key: "TECS_INTEG_GAIN", description: "Controller integrator", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.0 0.5", increment: "0.02", documentation: "This is the integrator gain on the control loop. Increase to increase the rate at which speed and height offsets are trimmed out"},
{name: "TECS_VERT_ACC", key: "TECS_VERT_ACC", description: "Vertical Acceleration Limit (metres/sec^2)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "1.0 10.0", increment: "0.5", documentation: "This is the maximum vertical acceleration either up or down that the  controller will use to correct speed or height errors."},
{name: "TECS_HGT_OMEGA", key: "TECS_HGT_OMEGA", description: "Height complementary filter frequency (radians/sec)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "1.0 5.0", increment: "0.05", documentation: "This is the cross-over frequency of the complementary filter used to fuse vertical acceleration and baro alt to obtain an estimate of height rate and height."},
{name: "TECS_SPD_OMEGA", key: "TECS_SPD_OMEGA", description: "Speed complementary filter frequency (radians/sec)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.5 2.0", increment: "0.05", documentation: "This is the cross-over frequency of the complementary filter used to fuse longitudinal acceleration and airspeed to obtain a lower noise and lag estimate of airspeed."},
{name: "TECS_RLL2THR", key: "TECS_RLL2THR", description: "Bank angle compensation gain", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "5.0 30.0", increment: "1.0", documentation: "Increasing this gain turn increases the amount of throttle that will be used to compensate for the additional drag created by turning. Ideally this should be set to approximately 10 x the extra sink rate in m/s created by a 45 degree bank turn. Increase this gain if the aircraft initially loses energy in turns and reduce if the aircraft initially gains energy in turns. Efficient high aspect-ratio aircraft (eg powered sailplanes) can use a lower value, whereas inefficient low aspect-ratio models (eg delta wings) can use a higher value."},
{name: "TECS_SPDWEIGHT", key: "TECS_SPDWEIGHT", description: "Weighting applied to speed control", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.0 2.0", increment: "0.1", documentation: "This parameter adjusts the amount of weighting that the pitch control applies to speed vs height errors. Setting it to 0.0 will cause the pitch control to control height and ignore speed errors. This will normally improve height accuracy but give larger airspeed errors. Setting it to 2.0 will cause the pitch control loop to control speed and ignore height errors. This will normally reduce airsped errors, but give larger height errors.	A value of 1.0 gives a balanced response and is the default."},
{name: "TECS_PTCH_DAMP", key: "TECS_PTCH_DAMP", description: "Controller pitch damping", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.1 1.0", increment: "0.1", documentation: "This is the damping gain for the pitch demand loop. Increase to add damping  to correct for oscillations in speed and height."},
{name: "TECS_SINK_MAX", key: "TECS_SINK_MAX", description: "Maximum Descent Rate (metres/sec)", value: "", user: "User", range: "0.0 20.0", increment: "0.1", documentation: "This sets the maximum descent rate that the controller will use.  If this value is too large, the aircraft will reach the pitch angle limit first and be unable to achieve the descent rate. This should be set to a value that can be achieved at the lower pitch angle limit."},
{name: "TECS_LAND_ARSPD", key: "TECS_LAND_ARSPD", description: "Airspeed during landing approach (m/s)", value: "", user: "User", range: "-1 127", increment: "1", documentation: "When performing an autonomus landing, this value is used as the goal airspeed during approach.  Note that this parameter is not useful if your platform does not have an airspeed sensor (use TECS_LAND_THR instead).  If negative then this value is not used during landing."},
{name: "TECS_LAND_THR", key: "TECS_LAND_THR", description: "Cruise throttle during landing approach (percentage)", value: "", user: "User", range: "-1 100", increment: "0.1", documentation: "Use this parameter instead of LAND_ARSPD if your platform does not have an airspeed sensor.  It is the cruise throttle during landing approach.  If this value is negative then it is disabled and TECS_LAND_ARSPD is used instead."},
{name: "TECS_LAND_SPDWGT", key: "TECS_LAND_SPDWGT", description: "Weighting applied to speed control during landing.", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "-1.0 2.0", increment: "0.1", documentation: "Same as SPDWEIGHT parameter, with the exception that this parameter is applied during landing flight stages.  A value closer to 2 will result in the plane ignoring height error during landing and our experience has been that the plane will therefore keep the nose up -- sometimes good for a glider landing (with the side effect that you will likely glide a ways past the landing point).  A value closer to 0 results in the plane ignoring speed error -- use caution when lowering the value below 1 -- ignoring speed could result in a stall. Values between 0 and 2 are valid values for a fixed landing weight. When using -1 the weight will be scaled during the landing. At the start of the landing approach it starts with TECS_SPDWEIGHT and scales down to 0 by the time you reach the land point. Example: Halfway down the landing approach youll effectively have a weight of TECS_SPDWEIGHT/2."},
{name: "TECS_PITCH_MAX", key: "TECS_PITCH_MAX", description: "Maximum pitch in auto flight", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0 45", increment: "1", documentation: "This controls maximum pitch up in automatic throttle modes. If this is set to zero then LIM_PITCH_MAX is used instead. The purpose of this parameter is to allow the use of a smaller pitch range when in automatic flight than what is used in FBWA mode."},
{name: "TECS_PITCH_MIN", key: "TECS_PITCH_MIN", description: "Minimum pitch in auto flight", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "-45 0", increment: "1", documentation: "This controls minimum pitch in automatic throttle modes. If this is set to zero then LIM_PITCH_MIN is used instead. The purpose of this parameter is to allow the use of a smaller pitch range when in automatic flight than what is used in FBWA mode. Note that TECS_PITCH_MIN should be a negative number."},
{name: "TECS_LAND_SINK", key: "TECS_LAND_SINK", description: "Sink rate for final landing stage", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.0 2.0", increment: "0.1", documentation: "The sink rate in meters/second for the final stage of landing."},
{name: "TECS_LAND_TCONST", key: "TECS_LAND_TCONST", description: "Land controller time constant (sec)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "1.0 5.0", increment: "0.2", documentation: "This is the time constant of the TECS control algorithm when in final landing stage of flight. It should be smaller than TECS_TIME_CONST to allow for faster flare"},
{name: "TECS_LAND_DAMP", key: "TECS_LAND_DAMP", description: "Controller sink rate to pitch gain during flare", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.1 1.0", increment: "0.1", documentation: "This is the sink rate gain for the pitch demand loop when in final landing stage of flight. It should be larger than TECS_PTCH_DAMP to allow for better sink rate control during flare."},
{name: "TECS_LAND_PMAX", key: "TECS_LAND_PMAX", description: "Maximum pitch during final stage of landing", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "-5 40", increment: "1", documentation: "This limits the pitch used during the final stage of automatic landing. During the final landing stage most planes need to keep their pitch small to avoid stalling. A maximum of 10 degrees is usually good. A value of zero means to use the normal pitch limits."},
{name: "TECS_APPR_SMAX", key: "TECS_APPR_SMAX", description: "Sink rate max for landing approach stage", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.0 20.0", increment: "0.1", units: "m/s", documentation: "The sink rate max for the landing approach stage of landing. This will need to be large for steep landing approaches especially when using reverse thrust. If 0, then use TECS_SINK_MAX."},
{name: "TECS_LAND_SRC", key: "TECS_LAND_SRC", description: "Land sink rate change", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "-2.0 2.0", increment: "0.1", units: "m/s/m", documentation: "When zero, the flare sink rate (TECS_LAND_SINK) is a fixed sink demand. With this enabled the flare sinkrate will increase/decrease the flare sink demand as you get further beyond the LAND waypoint. Has no effect before the waypoint. This value is added to TECS_LAND_SINK proportional to distance traveled after wp. Note that if a FS_TERM_PIN is set then the heartbeat pin will continue to cycle at 10Hz when termination is activated, to allow the termination board to distinguish between autopilot crash and termination."},
{name: "AFS_WP_COMMS", key: "AFS_WP_COMMS", description: "Comms Waypoint", value: "", user: "Advanced", documentation: "Waypoint number to navigate to on comms loss"},
{name: "AFS_GPS_LOSS", key: "AFS_GPS_LOSS", description: "GPS Loss Waypoint", value: "", user: "Advanced", documentation: "Waypoint number to navigate to on GPS lock loss"},
{name: "AFS_TERMINATE", key: "AFS_TERMINATE", description: "Force Terminate", value: "", user: "Advanced", documentation: "Can be set in flight to force termination of the heartbeat signal"},
{name: "AFS_TERM_ACTION", key: "AFS_TERM_ACTION", description: "Terminate action", value: "", user: "Advanced", documentation: "This can be used to force an action on flight termination. Normally this is handled by an external failsafe board, but you can setup APM to handle it here. If set to 0 (which is the default) then no extra action is taken. If set to the magic value 42 then the plane will deliberately crash itself by setting maximum throws on all surfaces, and zero throttle"},
{name: "AFS_TERM_PIN", key: "AFS_TERM_PIN", description: "Terminate Pin", value: "", user: "Advanced", documentation: "This sets a digital output pin to set high on flight termination"},
{name: "AFS_AMSL_LIMIT", key: "AFS_AMSL_LIMIT", description: "AMSL limit", value: "", user: "Advanced", units: "meters", documentation: "This sets the AMSL (above mean sea level) altitude limit. If the pressure altitude determined by QNH exceeds this limit then flight termination will be forced. Note that this limit is in meters, whereas pressure altitude limits are often quoted in feet. A value of zero disables the pressure altitude limit."},
{name: "AFS_AMSL_ERR_GPS", key: "AFS_AMSL_ERR_GPS", description: "Error margin for GPS based AMSL limit", value: "", user: "Advanced", units: "meters", documentation: "This sets margin for error in GPS derived altitude limit. This error margin is only used if the barometer has failed. If the barometer fails then the GPS will be used to enforce the AMSL_LIMIT, but this margin will be subtracted from the AMSL_LIMIT first, to ensure that even with the given amount of GPS altitude error the pressure altitude is not breached. OBC users should set this to comply with their D2 safety case. A value of -1 will mean that barometer failure will lead to immediate termination."},
{name: "AFS_QNH_PRESSURE", key: "AFS_QNH_PRESSURE", description: "QNH pressure", value: "", user: "Advanced", units: "millibar", documentation: "This sets the QNH pressure in millibars to be used for pressure altitude in the altitude limit. A value of zero disables the altitude limit."},
{name: "AFS_ENABLE", key: "AFS_ENABLE", description: "Enable Advanced Failsafe", value: "", user: "Advanced", documentation: "This enables the advanced failsafe system. If this is set to zero (disable) then all the other AFS options have no effect"},
{name: "AFS_RC_FAIL_MS", key: "AFS_RC_FAIL_MS", description: "RC failure time", value: "", user: "Advanced", documentation: "This is the time in milliseconds in manual mode that failsafe termination will activate if RC input is lost. For the OBC rules this should be 1500. Use 0 to disable."},
{name: "AFS_MAX_GPS_LOSS", key: "AFS_MAX_GPS_LOSS", description: "Maximum number of GPS loss events", value: "", user: "Advanced", documentation: "Maximum number of GPS loss events before the aircraft stops returning to mission on GPS recovery. Use zero to allow for any number of GPS loss events."},
{name: "AFS_MAX_COM_LOSS", key: "AFS_MAX_COM_LOSS", description: "Maximum number of comms loss events", value: "", user: "Advanced", documentation: "Maximum number of comms loss events before the aircraft stops returning to mission on comms recovery. Use zero to allow for any number of comms loss events."},
{name: "FLOW_ENABLE", key: "FLOW_ENABLE", description: "Optical flow enable/disable", value: "", user: "Standard", values: {"0": "Disabled", " 1": "Enabled"},
documentation: "Setting this to Enabled(1) will enable optical flow. Setting this to Disabled(0) will disable optical flow"},
{name: "FLOW_FXSCALER", key: "FLOW_FXSCALER", description: "X axis optical flow scale factor correction", value: "", user: "Standard", range: "-200 +200", increment: "1", documentation: "This sets the parts per thousand scale factor correction applied to the flow sensor X axis optical rate. It can be used to correct for variations in effective focal length. Each positive increment of 1 increases the scale factor applied to the X axis optical flow reading by 0.1%. Negative values reduce the scale factor."},
{name: "FLOW_FYSCALER", key: "FLOW_FYSCALER", description: "Y axis optical flow scale factor correction", value: "", user: "Standard", range: "-200 +200", increment: "1", documentation: "This sets the parts per thousand scale factor correction applied to the flow sensor Y axis optical rate. It can be used to correct for variations in effective focal length. Each positive increment of 1 increases the scale factor applied to the Y axis optical flow reading by 0.1%. Negative values reduce the scale factor."},
{name: "FLOW_ORIENT_YAW", key: "FLOW_ORIENT_YAW", description: "Flow sensor yaw alignment", value: "", user: "Standard", range: "-18000 +18000", increment: "1", documentation: "Specifies the number of centi-degrees that the flow sensor is yawed relative to the vehicle. A sensor with its X-axis pointing to the right of the vehicle X axis has a positive yaw angle."},
{name: "MIS_TOTAL", key: "MIS_TOTAL", description: "Total mission commands", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0 32766", increment: "1", documentation: "The number of mission mission items that has been loaded by the ground station. Do not change this manually."},
{name: "MIS_RESTART", key: "MIS_RESTART", description: "Mission Restart when entering Auto mode", value: "", user: "", values: {"0": "Resume Mission", " 1": "Restart Mission"},
documentation: "Controls mission starting point when entering Auto mode (either restart from beginning of mission or resume from last command run)"},
{name: "RALLY_TOTAL", key: "RALLY_TOTAL", description: "Rally Total", value: "", user: "Advanced", documentation: "Number of rally points currently loaded"},
{name: "RALLY_LIMIT_KM", key: "RALLY_LIMIT_KM", description: "Rally Limit", value: "", user: "Advanced", increment: "0.1", units: "kilometers", documentation: "Maximum distance to rally point. If the closest rally point is more than this number of kilometers from the current position and the home location is closer than any of the rally points from the current position then do RTL to home rather than to the closest rally point. This prevents a leftover rally point from a different airfield being used accidentally. If this is set to 0 then the closest rally point is always used."},
{name: "RALLY_INCL_HOME", key: "RALLY_INCL_HOME", description: "Rally Include Home", value: "", user: "Standard", values: {"0": "DoNotIncludeHome", "1": "IncludeHome"},
documentation: "Controls if Home is included as a Rally point (i.e. as a safe landing place) for RTL"},
{name: "EKF_ENABLE", key: "EKF_ENABLE", description: "Enable EKF1", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "Disabled", " 1": "Enabled"},
documentation: "This enables EKF1 to be disabled when using alternative algorithms. When disabling it, the alternate EKF2 estimator must be enabled by setting EK2_ENABLED = 1 and flight control algorithms must be set to use the alternative estimator by setting AHRS_EKF_TYPE = 2."},
{name: "EKF_VELNE_NOISE", key: "EKF_VELNE_NOISE", description: "GPS horizontal velocity measurement noise scaler", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.05 5.0", increment: "0.05", documentation: "This is the scaler that is applied to the speed accuracy reported by the receiver to estimate the horizontal velocity observation noise. If the model of receiver used does not provide a speed accurcy estimate, then a speed acuracy of 1 is assumed. Increasing it reduces the weighting on these measurements."},
{name: "EKF_VELD_NOISE", key: "EKF_VELD_NOISE", description: "GPS vertical velocity measurement noise scaler", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.05 5.0", increment: "0.05", documentation: "This is the scaler that is applied to the speed accuracy reported by the receiver to estimate the vertical velocity observation noise. If the model of receiver used does not provide a speed accurcy estimate, then a speed acuracy of 1 is assumed. Increasing it reduces the weighting on this measurement."},
{name: "EKF_POSNE_NOISE", key: "EKF_POSNE_NOISE", description: "GPS horizontal position measurement noise (m)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.1 10.0", increment: "0.1", units: "meters", documentation: "This is the RMS value of noise in the GPS horizontal position measurements. Increasing it reduces the weighting on these measurements."},
{name: "EKF_ALT_NOISE", key: "EKF_ALT_NOISE", description: "Altitude measurement noise (m)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.1 10.0", increment: "0.1", units: "meters", documentation: "This is the RMS value of noise in the altitude measurement. Increasing it reduces the weighting on this measurement."},
{name: "EKF_MAG_NOISE", key: "EKF_MAG_NOISE", description: "Magnetometer measurement noise (Gauss)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.01 0.5", increment: "0.01", documentation: "This is the RMS value of noise in magnetometer measurements. Increasing it reduces the weighting on these measurements."},
{name: "EKF_EAS_NOISE", key: "EKF_EAS_NOISE", description: "Equivalent airspeed measurement noise (m/s)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.5 5.0", increment: "0.1", units: "m/s", documentation: "This is the RMS value of noise in equivalent airspeed measurements. Increasing it reduces the weighting on these measurements."},
{name: "EKF_WIND_PNOISE", key: "EKF_WIND_PNOISE", description: "Wind velocity process noise (m/s^2)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.01 1.0", increment: "0.1", documentation: "This noise controls the growth of wind state error estimates. Increasing it makes wind estimation faster and noisier."},
{name: "EKF_WIND_PSCALE", key: "EKF_WIND_PSCALE", description: "Height rate to wind procss noise scaler", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.0 1.0", increment: "0.1", documentation: "Increasing this parameter increases how rapidly the wind states adapt when changing altitude, but does make wind speed estimation noiser."},
{name: "EKF_GYRO_PNOISE", key: "EKF_GYRO_PNOISE", description: "Rate gyro noise (rad/s)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.001 0.05", increment: "0.001", units: "rad/s", documentation: "This noise controls the growth of estimated error due to gyro measurement errors excluding bias. Increasing it makes the flter trust the gyro measurements less and other measurements more."},
{name: "EKF_ACC_PNOISE", key: "EKF_ACC_PNOISE", description: "Accelerometer noise (m/s^2)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.05 1.0", increment: "0.01", units: "m/s/s", documentation: "This noise controls the growth of estimated error due to accelerometer measurement errors excluding bias. Increasing it makes the flter trust the accelerometer measurements less and other measurements more."},
{name: "EKF_GBIAS_PNOISE", key: "EKF_GBIAS_PNOISE", description: "Rate gyro bias process noise (rad/s)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.0000001 0.00001", units: "rad/s", documentation: "This noise controls the growth of gyro bias state error estimates. Increasing it makes rate gyro bias estimation faster and noisier."},
{name: "EKF_ABIAS_PNOISE", key: "EKF_ABIAS_PNOISE", description: "Accelerometer bias process noise (m/s^2)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.00001 0.001", units: "m/s/s", documentation: "This noise controls the growth of the vertical acelerometer bias state error estimate. Increasing it makes accelerometer bias estimation faster and noisier."},
{name: "EKF_MAGE_PNOISE", key: "EKF_MAGE_PNOISE", description: "Earth magnetic field process noise (gauss/s)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.0001 0.01", units: "gauss/s", documentation: "This noise controls the growth of earth magnetic field state error estimates. Increasing it makes earth magnetic field bias estimation faster and noisier."},
{name: "EKF_MAGB_PNOISE", key: "EKF_MAGB_PNOISE", description: "Body magnetic field process noise (gauss/s)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.0001 0.01", units: "gauss/s", documentation: "This noise controls the growth of body magnetic field state error estimates. Increasing it makes compass offset estimation faster and noisier."},
{name: "EKF_VEL_DELAY", key: "EKF_VEL_DELAY", description: "GPS velocity measurement delay (msec)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0 500", increment: "10", units: "milliseconds", documentation: "This is the number of msec that the GPS velocity measurements lag behind the inertial measurements."},
{name: "EKF_POS_DELAY", key: "EKF_POS_DELAY", description: "GPS position measurement delay (msec)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0 500", increment: "10", units: "milliseconds", documentation: "This is the number of msec that the GPS position measurements lag behind the inertial measurements."},
{name: "EKF_GPS_TYPE", key: "EKF_GPS_TYPE", description: "GPS mode control", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "GPS 3D Vel and 2D Pos", " 1": "GPS 2D vel and 2D pos", " 2": "GPS 2D pos", " 3": "No GPS use optical flow"},
documentation: "This parameter controls use of GPS measurements : 0 = use 3D velocity & 2D position, 1 = use 2D velocity and 2D position, 2 = use 2D position, 3 = use no GPS (optical flow will be used if available)"},
{name: "EKF_VEL_GATE", key: "EKF_VEL_GATE", description: "GPS velocity measurement gate size", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "1 100", increment: "1", documentation: "This parameter sets the number of standard deviations applied to the GPS velocity measurement innovation consistency check. Decreasing it makes it more likely that good measurements willbe rejected. Increasing it makes it more likely that bad measurements will be accepted."},
{name: "EKF_POS_GATE", key: "EKF_POS_GATE", description: "GPS position measurement gate size", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "1 100", increment: "1", documentation: "This parameter sets the number of standard deviations applied to the GPS position measurement innovation consistency check. Decreasing it makes it more likely that good measurements will be rejected. Increasing it makes it more likely that bad measurements will be accepted."},
{name: "EKF_HGT_GATE", key: "EKF_HGT_GATE", description: "Height measurement gate size", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "1 100", increment: "1", documentation: "This parameter sets the number of standard deviations applied to the height measurement innovation consistency check. Decreasing it makes it more likely that good measurements will be rejected. Increasing it makes it more likely that bad measurements will be accepted."},
{name: "EKF_MAG_GATE", key: "EKF_MAG_GATE", description: "Magnetometer measurement gate size", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "1 100", increment: "1", documentation: "This parameter sets the number of standard deviations applied to the magnetometer measurement innovation consistency check. Decreasing it makes it more likely that good measurements will be rejected. Increasing it makes it more likely that bad measurements will be accepted."},
{name: "EKF_EAS_GATE", key: "EKF_EAS_GATE", description: "Airspeed measurement gate size", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "1 100", increment: "1", documentation: "This parameter sets the number of standard deviations applied to the airspeed measurement innovation consistency check. Decreasing it makes it more likely that good measurements will be rejected. Increasing it makes it more likely that bad measurements will be accepted."},
{name: "EKF_MAG_CAL", key: "EKF_MAG_CAL", description: "Magnetometer calibration mode", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "Speed and Height", "1": "Acceleration", "2": "Never", "3": "Always"},
documentation: "EKF_MAG_CAL = 0 enables calibration based on flying speed and altitude and is the default setting for Plane users. EKF_MAG_CAL = 1 enables calibration based on manoeuvre level and is the default setting for Copter and Rover users. EKF_MAG_CAL = 2 prevents magnetometer calibration regardless of flight condition and is recommended if in-flight magnetometer calibration is unreliable."},
{name: "EKF_GLITCH_ACCEL", key: "EKF_GLITCH_ACCEL", description: "GPS glitch accel gate size (cm/s^2)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "100 500", increment: "50", documentation: "This parameter controls the maximum amount of difference in horizontal acceleration between the value predicted by the filter and the value measured by the GPS before the GPS position data is rejected. If this value is set too low, then valid GPS data will be regularly discarded, and the position accuracy will degrade. If this parameter is set too high, then large GPS glitches will cause large rapid changes in position."},
{name: "EKF_GLITCH_RAD", key: "EKF_GLITCH_RAD", description: "GPS glitch radius gate size (m)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "10 50", increment: "5", units: "meters", documentation: "This parameter controls the maximum amount of difference in horizontal position (in m) between the value predicted by the filter and the value measured by the GPS before the long term glitch protection logic is activated and the filter states are reset to the new GPS position. Position steps smaller than this value will be temporarily ignored, but will then be accepted and the filter will move to the new position. Position steps larger than this value will be ignored initially, but the filter will then apply an offset to the GPS position measurement."},
{name: "EKF_GND_GRADIENT", key: "EKF_GND_GRADIENT", description: "Terrain Gradient % RMS", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "1 50", increment: "1", documentation: "This parameter sets the RMS terrain gradient percentage assumed by the terrain height estimation. Terrain height can be estimated using optical flow and/or range finder sensor data if fitted. Smaller values cause the terrain height estimate to be slower to respond to changes in measurement. Larger values casue the terrain height estimate to be faster to respond, but also more noisy. Generally this value can be reduced if operating over very flat terrain and increased if operating over uneven terrain."},
{name: "EKF_FLOW_NOISE", key: "EKF_FLOW_NOISE", description: "Optical flow measurement noise (rad/s)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.05 1.0", increment: "0.05", units: "rad/s", documentation: "This is the RMS value of noise and errors in optical flow measurements. Increasing it reduces the weighting on these measurements."},
{name: "EKF_FLOW_GATE", key: "EKF_FLOW_GATE", description: "Optical Flow measurement gate size", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "1 100", increment: "1", documentation: "This parameter sets the number of standard deviations applied to the optical flow innovation consistency check. Decreasing it makes it more likely that good measurements will be rejected. Increasing it makes it more likely that bad measurements will be accepted."},
{name: "EKF_FLOW_DELAY", key: "EKF_FLOW_DELAY", description: "Optical Flow measurement delay (msec)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0 500", increment: "10", units: "milliseconds", documentation: "This is the number of msec that the optical flow measurements lag behind the inertial measurements. It is the time from the end of the optical flow averaging period and does not include the time delay due to the 100msec of averaging within the flow sensor."},
{name: "EKF_RNG_GATE", key: "EKF_RNG_GATE", description: "Range finder measurement gate size", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "1 100", increment: "1", documentation: "This parameter sets the number of standard deviations applied to the range finder innovation consistency check. Decreasing it makes it more likely that good measurements will be rejected. Increasing it makes it more likely that bad measurements will be accepted."},
{name: "EKF_MAX_FLOW", key: "EKF_MAX_FLOW", description: "Maximum valid optical flow rate", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "1.0 4.0", increment: "0.1", documentation: "This parameter sets the magnitude maximum optical flow rate in rad/sec that will be accepted by the filter"},
{name: "EKF_FALLBACK", key: "EKF_FALLBACK", description: "Fallback strictness", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "Trust EKF more", " 1": "Trust DCM more"},
documentation: "This parameter controls the conditions necessary to trigger a fallback to DCM and INAV. A value of 1 will cause fallbacks to occur on loss of GPS and other conditions. A value of 0 will trust the EKF more."},
{name: "EKF_ALT_SOURCE", key: "EKF_ALT_SOURCE", description: "Primary height source", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "Use Baro", " 1": "Use Range Finder"},
documentation: "This parameter controls which height sensor is used by the EKF during optical flow navigation (when EKF_GPS_TYPE = 3). A value of will 0 cause it to always use baro altitude. A value of 1 will casue it to use range finder if available."},
{name: "EKF_GPS_CHECK", key: "EKF_GPS_CHECK", description: "GPS preflight check", value: "", user: "Advanced", bitmask: "0:nsats,1:hdop,2:speed error,3:horiz pos error,4:yaw error,5:pos drift,6:vert speed,7:horiz speed", documentation: "1 byte bitmap of GPS preflight checks to perform. Set to 0 to bypass all checks. Set to 255 perform all checks. Set to 3 to check just the number of satellites and HDoP. Set to 31 for the most rigorous checks that will still allow checks to pass when the copter is moving, eg launch from a boat."},
{name: "EK2_ENABLE", key: "EK2_ENABLE", description: "Enable EKF2", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "Disabled", " 1": "Enabled"},
documentation: "This enables EKF2. Enabling EKF2 only makes the maths run, it does not mean it will be used for flight control. To use it for flight control set AHRS_EKF_TYPE=2. A reboot or restart will need to be performed after changing the value of EK2_ENABLE for it to take effect."},
{name: "EK2_GPS_TYPE", key: "EK2_GPS_TYPE", description: "GPS mode control", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "GPS 3D Vel and 2D Pos", " 1": "GPS 2D vel and 2D pos", " 2": "GPS 2D pos", " 3": "No GPS use optical flow"},
documentation: "This controls use of GPS measurements : 0 = use 3D velocity & 2D position, 1 = use 2D velocity and 2D position, 2 = use 2D position, 3 = use no GPS (optical flow will be used if available)"},
{name: "EK2_VELNE_NOISE", key: "EK2_VELNE_NOISE", description: "GPS horizontal velocity measurement noise (m/s)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.05 5.0", increment: "0.05", units: "m/s", documentation: "This sets a lower limit on the speed accuracy reported by the GPS receiver that is used to set horizontal velocity observation noise. If the model of receiver used does not provide a speed accurcy estimate, then the parameter value will be used. Increasing it reduces the weighting of the GPS horizontal velocity measurements."},
{name: "EK2_VELD_NOISE", key: "EK2_VELD_NOISE", description: "GPS vertical velocity measurement noise (m/s)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.05 5.0", increment: "0.05", units: "m/s", documentation: "This sets a lower limit on the speed accuracy reported by the GPS receiver that is used to set vertical velocity observation noise. If the model of receiver used does not provide a speed accurcy estimate, then the parameter value will be used. Increasing it reduces the weighting of the GPS vertical velocity measurements."},
{name: "EK2_VEL_GATE", key: "EK2_VEL_GATE", description: "GPS velocity innovation gate size", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "100 1000", increment: "25", documentation: "This sets the percentage number of standard deviations applied to the GPS velocity measurement innovation consistency check. Decreasing it makes it more likely that good measurements willbe rejected. Increasing it makes it more likely that bad measurements will be accepted."},
{name: "EK2_POSNE_NOISE", key: "EK2_POSNE_NOISE", description: "GPS horizontal position measurement noise (m)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.1 10.0", increment: "0.1", units: "m", documentation: "This sets the GPS horizontal position observation noise. Increasing it reduces the weighting of GPS horizontal position measurements."},
{name: "EK2_POS_GATE", key: "EK2_POS_GATE", description: "GPS position measurement gate size", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "100 1000", increment: "25", documentation: "This sets the percentage number of standard deviations applied to the GPS position measurement innovation consistency check. Decreasing it makes it more likely that good measurements will be rejected. Increasing it makes it more likely that bad measurements will be accepted."},
{name: "EK2_GLITCH_RAD", key: "EK2_GLITCH_RAD", description: "GPS glitch radius gate size (m)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "10 100", increment: "5", units: "m", documentation: "This controls the maximum radial uncertainty in position between the value predicted by the filter and the value measured by the GPS before the filter position and velocity states are reset to the GPS. Making this value larger allows the filter to ignore larger GPS glitches but also means that non-GPS errors such as IMU and compass can create a larger error in position before the filter is forced back to the GPS position."},
{name: "EK2_GPS_DELAY", key: "EK2_GPS_DELAY", description: "GPS measurement delay (msec)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0 250", increment: "10", units: "msec", documentation: "This is the number of msec that the GPS measurements lag behind the inertial measurements."},
{name: "EK2_ALT_SOURCE", key: "EK2_ALT_SOURCE", description: "Primary height source", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "Use Baro", " 1": "Use Range Finder", " 2": "Use GPS"},
documentation: "This parameter controls which height sensor is used by the EKF. If the selected optionn cannot be used, it will default to Baro as the primary height source. Setting 0 will use the baro altitude at all times. Setting 1 uses the range finder and is only available in combination with optical flow navigation (EK2_GPS_TYPE = 3). Setting 2 uses GPS."},
{name: "EK2_ALT_NOISE", key: "EK2_ALT_NOISE", description: "Altitude measurement noise (m)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.1 10.0", increment: "0.1", units: "m", documentation: "This is the RMS value of noise in the altitude measurement. Increasing it reduces the weighting of the baro measurement and will make the filter respond more slowly to baro measurement errors, but will make it more sensitive to GPS and accelerometer errors."},
{name: "EK2_HGT_GATE", key: "EK2_HGT_GATE", description: "Height measurement gate size", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "100 1000", increment: "25", documentation: "This sets the percentage number of standard deviations applied to the height measurement innovation consistency check. Decreasing it makes it more likely that good measurements will be rejected. Increasing it makes it more likely that bad measurements will be accepted."},
{name: "EK2_HGT_DELAY", key: "EK2_HGT_DELAY", description: "Height measurement delay (msec)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0 250", increment: "10", units: "msec", documentation: "This is the number of msec that the Height measurements lag behind the inertial measurements."},
{name: "EK2_MAG_NOISE", key: "EK2_MAG_NOISE", description: "Magnetometer measurement noise (Gauss)", value: "", user: "Advanced", range: "0.01 0.5", increment: "0.01", units: "gauss", documentation: "This is the RMS value of noise in magnetometer measurements. Increasing it reduces the weighting on these measurements."},
{name: "EK2_MAG_CAL", key: "EK2_MAG_CAL", description: "Magnetometer calibration mode", value: "", user: "Advanced", values: {"0": "When flying", "1": "When manoeuvring", "2": "Never", "3": "After first climb yaw reset", "4": "Always"},
documentation: "EKF_MAG_CAL = 0 enables calibration when airborne and is the default setting for Plane users. EKF_MAG_CAL = 1 enables calibration when manoeuvreing. EKF_MAG_CAL = 2 prevents magnetometer calibration regardless of flight condition, is recommended if the external magnetic field is varying and is the default for rovers. EKF_MAG_CAL = 3 enables calibration when the first in-air field and yaw reset has completed and is the default for copters. EKF_MAG_CAL = 4 enables calibration all the time. This determines when the filter will use the 3-axis magnetometer fusion model that estimates both earth and body fixed magnetic field states. This model is only suitable for use when the external magnetic field environment is stable."},
